<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1225,1574]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">
The 
<typeStatus box="[254,302,1226,1250]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">type</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName box="[468,873,1225,1250]" class="Insecta" family="Mantispidae" genus="Mantispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatella" subGenus="Trichoscelia">
<emphasis box="[468,873,1225,1250]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Mantispa (Trichoscelia) fasciatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows the anal region of forewing dark amber pigmented. The specimens studied here show the same region orange and the medial transverse stripe narrower (
<figureCitation box="[159,242,1297,1322]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1666,1688]" captionTargetBox="[203,1383,629,1643]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[203,1384,629,1644]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 16. Type material: a, Mantispa (Trichoscelia) eurydella Westwood, habitus holotype female (Photo by Amoret Spooner, Oxford University Museum of Natural History); b, Mantispa batesella Westwood, habitus syntype male (Photo by: Amoret Spooner, Oxford University Museum); c, Mantispa (Trichoscelia) fasciatella Westwood, habitus holotype female (Photo by: Zoe Simmons, Oxford University Museum)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/236831/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,242,1297,1322]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
c).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1225,1574]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">
<taxonomicName box="[199,389,1333,1358]" class="Insecta" family="Mantispidae" genus="Plega" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatella">
<emphasis box="[199,389,1333,1358]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Plega fasciatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a mimetic pattern of orange and black bands, which is generally characteristics of many braconines (Braconinae) possessing abdominal glands which produce a repulsive substance in the abdomen. Interestingly, several 
<taxonomicName authority="Tenthredinoidea" authorityName="Tenthredinoidea" box="[406,782,1405,1430]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ichneumonidae, Tenthredinoidea</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[804,898,1405,1430]" class="Insecta" family="Argidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Argidae</taxonomicName>
, especially of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1210,1300,1405,1430]" class="Insecta" family="Argidae" genus="Scobina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1210,1300,1405,1430]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Scobina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and some 
<taxonomicName box="[151,324,1441,1466]" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tenthredinidae</taxonomicName>
), and some 
<taxonomicName box="[457,591,1441,1466]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chalcididae</taxonomicName>
also possess this pattern. Even outside of 
<taxonomicName box="[1068,1223,1442,1466]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
, some 
<taxonomicName box="[1302,1432,1441,1466]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Reduviidae</taxonomicName>
, known for their aggressive nature, are characterized by a similar colour pattern (Bolivar R. Garcete-Barret, pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
